《-{zh-hant:'''大亨小傳''';zh-hans:'''了不起的盖茨比'''}-》（{{lang-en|''The Great Gatsby''}}，又譯《-{zh-hant:'''了不起的蓋茨比''';zh-hans:'''大亨小传'''}-》），出版于1925年，是美國作家[[弗朗西斯·斯科特·菲茨杰拉德|弗朗西斯·斯科特·菲茨杰拉德]]所寫的一部以1920年代的[[紐約市|紐約市]]及[[長島_(紐約州)|長島]]為背景的[[中篇小說|中篇小說]]，被視為[[美國文學|美國文學]]“[[爵士時代|爵士時代]]”的象徵。故事主要講述了年輕而神秘的百萬富翁{{link-en|傑·蓋茨比|Jay Gatsby}}對黛西·布卡南的执着追求。小說是菲茨杰拉德最伟大的作品，探討了墮落、理想主義、變革阻礙、社會巨變、放蕩；爲爵士時代和[[咆哮的二十年代|咆哮的二十年代]]進行了深度描繪，普遍認爲是對[[美國夢|美國夢]]的警醒。<ref name=karolides2011>{{cite book |last1=Karolides |first1=Nicholas J. |last2=Bald |first2=Margaret |last3=Sova |first3=Dawn B. |title=120 Banned Books: Censorship Histories of World Literature |edition=Second |year=2011 |publisher=Checkmark Books |isbn=978-0-8160-8232-2 |page=499 |quote=Rather than a celebration of such decadence, the novel functions as a cautionary tale in which an unhappy fate is inevitable for the poor and striving individual, and the rich are allowed to continue without penalty their careless treatment of others' lives.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Hoover |first=Bob |title='The Great Gatsby' still challenges myth of American Dream |date=10 May 2013 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/movies/great-gatsby-still-challenges-myth-of-american-dream-687050/ |publisher=''[[Pittsburgh_Post-Gazette|Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' |accessdate=10 May 2013 |archive-date=2013-08-27 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6JCAXtwWX?url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/movies/great-gatsby-still-challenges-myth-of-american-dream-687050/ |dead-url=no }}</ref>

菲茨杰拉德參加了長島北岸的宴會，在1923年著手小說的創作，用他的話來說，“一些''新穎的''——一些非凡的、美妙的、單純的、雜亂的形式。”<ref>{{cite web |others=Images by Gareth M. |title=Something Extraordinary |url=http://www.lettersofnote.com/2012/01/something-extraordinary.html |work=Letters of Note |publisher=lettersofnote.com |accessdate=24 May 2013 |date=25 March 2013 |archive-date=2013-08-27 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6JCAZ2Anr?url=http://www.lettersofnote.com/2012/01/something-extraordinary.html |dead-url=yes }}</ref>然而，菲茨杰拉德的進度緩慢，在完成第一稿後于1924年前往[[藍色海岸|藍色海岸]]。他的編輯[[麥克斯威爾·柏金斯|麥克斯威爾·柏金斯]]認爲故事太暧昧，說服作者在第二個冬天將故事修訂。菲茨杰拉德對小說的標題感到迷茫，曾經一度將其命名爲《西卵的特立馬喬》<ref>''Trimalchio in West Egg''</ref>。

菲茨傑拉德是当时的畅销书作家，但他希望《了不起的盖茨比》能成为传世之作。查理斯·斯克裏布納之子公司出版了該小說后，评论界有褒有贬，而且销量不佳——菲茨杰拉德在世時的總銷量都少于二萬四千本。菲茨傑拉德很失望，于1940年含恨而終。小說在二战时流行开来，受到前线战士的欢迎，其後更成爲高中、大學文學課的必读作品。今天，《了不起的盖茨比》被公认为美國文學的經典{{le|傑作|Masterpiece}}。1998年，現代圖書館編輯委員會投票，評選其爲{{le|最偉大的美國小說|Great American Novel}}和最佳英語小說的第二名<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Best Novels|url=http://www.modernlibrary.com/top-100/100-best-novels/|publisher=Modern Library|accessdate=14 May 2014|archive-date=2015-11-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123233204/http://www.modernlibrary.com/top-100/100-best-novels/|dead-url=no}}</ref>；随后入选2005年时代周刊百本最佳英文小说<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.time.com/time/2005/100books/ |title=《时代周刊》百佳英文小说 |accessdate=2009-06-24 |archive-date=2009-05-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515000848/http://www.time.com/time/2005/100books/ |dead-url=no }}</ref>。

本书有許多中文翻譯版本，書名也有許多譯法：如《永恆之戀》（黃淑慎譯，1954年）、《大哉！蓋世比》（王潤華、淡瑩譯，1969年）、《大亨-{}-小傳》（[[喬治高|喬治高]]（高克毅）譯，1970年）、《大亨──凱士畢》（丁士奇譯，1971年）、《了不起的-{}-盖茨比》（[[巫宁坤|巫宁坤]]译，1982年）等。

== 歷史 ==
{{further|咆哮的二十年代|爵士時代}}
《了不起的盖茨比》的背景設在1922年興盛的長島，就美國[[咆哮的二十年代|咆哮的二十年代]]以社會批判的角度進行了敘述。在當時，經濟飛速發展，流行爵士樂、輕佻文化、販賣私酒、犯罪率高，都在小說中刻画出来。菲茨杰拉德利用二十年代的社會發展爲蓋茨比創造了鋪墊，從簡單的細節，如汽車，到更加宽泛的主題，如用盖茨比贩私酒暴富暗喻当时的犯罪文化等。<ref name="Bruccoli 2000 53–54">{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2000|pp=53–54}}</ref>菲茨杰拉德通过叙述一个易使读者产生共鸣、不随时代褪色的故事，揭露咆哮的二十年代浮华社会背後的真相。<ref>{{Cite book |last=Gross |first=Dalton |title=Understanding the Great Gatsby: A Student Casebook to Issues, Sources, and Historical Documents |year=1998 |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, Connecticut |page=167}}</ref>

菲茨杰拉德曾經在長島北岸的莊園參加了宴會，這爲小说背景提供了靈感。迄今，到底哪一所莊園才是故事靈感的來源地众说纷纭。一种说法是Land's End，这是一所著名的黃金海岸公館（Gold Coast Mansion）。<ref>{{cite web|last=Kellogg|first=Carolyn|title=Last gasp of the Gatsby house|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2011/04/last-gasp-of-the-gatsby-house.html|work=Jacket Copy|publisher=[[Los_Angeles_Times|Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=26 April 2013|archive-date=2021-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210113064037/https://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2011/04/last-gasp-of-the-Gatsby-house.html|dead-url=no}}</ref>作者早年生活也在故事中有所反映。菲茨杰拉德是明尼蘇達州人，和尼克一樣，他曾就讀于[[常春藤盟校|常春藤盟校]]之一：普林斯顿大学（尼克為[[耶魯大學|耶魯大學]]畢業）。菲茨杰拉德也與傑·蓋茨比有些類似，他在随军驻扎時墜入愛河，並努力試圖證明自己是位合格的戀人，结果失望一生。菲茨杰拉德19岁时擔任[[少尉|少尉]]，駐紮在[[阿拉巴馬蒙特哥馬利|阿拉巴馬蒙特哥馬利]]的[[謝爾丹營|謝爾丹營]]。他在那裏与十七歲的富家女杰内瓦·金相恋，但因为地位低微，被对方的父亲严词拒绝。22岁时，他與年僅十七歲的風流少女[[塞爾達·賽爾|塞爾達·賽爾]]（Zelda Sayre）相戀。塞爾達答應嫁給他，但由于她瘋狂拜金、貪圖享樂，又悔婚了，直到菲茨杰拉德的第一本畅销小说出版后他们才结婚。<ref name=sparknotes1>{{cite web |author=SparkNotes Editors |title=The Great Gatsby: Context |publisher=SparkNotes |url=http://www.sparknotes.com/lit/gatsby/context.html |accessdate=2013-11-25 |archive-date=2018-01-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103140419/http://www.sparknotes.com/lit/gatsby/context.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>像故事中的尼克一樣，菲茨杰拉德認爲這種新生活充滿激情和誘惑；和蓋茨比一樣，他對財富頂禮膜拜。<ref name="sparknotes1"/>在許多地方上，《了不起的蓋茨比》反映了菲茨杰拉德試圖直面自己对爵士時代充滿矛盾的心態。與蓋茨比相似，即使姑娘的所作所爲将菲茨杰拉德引向他所鄙夷的一切，但她代表着菲茨杰拉德所爱慕的一切，引诱他努力向前却又不断失去。<ref name="sparknotes1"/>

== 內容簡介 ==
小說主要事件發生在1922年夏。[[耶魯大學|耶魯大學]]畢業生、一戰退伍軍人尼克·卡拉威（也是小说叙述人）從中西部来到紐約，靠販卖债券維生。他在長島的西卵村租住了一間小屋，与蓋茨比为鄰。傑·蓋茨比是一個年輕、神秘的百萬富翁，经常舉辦豪華宴會，却很少出头露面；有許多人到他那裏去吃喝，他始終是一個孤獨的人。尼克驅車到東卵村拜访表妹黛西·費伊·布坎南，她丈夫湯姆·布坎南是尼克的大學同學。他們將尼克介紹給喬丹·貝克小姐，她是位充滿魅力却略带自私的青年高爾夫球手；尼克认为自己爱上了她。她告訴尼克，湯姆有外遇，叫默特爾·威爾遜，住在“[[法拉盛草原可乐娜公园|灰燼谷]]”：西卵村和紐約城之間的工業垃圾場。不久，尼克和湯姆、默特爾前往他们幽会的公寓，舉行放蕩的狂歡會。默特爾几度提起黛西的名字，湯姆在憤怒中打扁了默特爾的鼻子。[[File:Plaza_Hotel_NYC.jpg|thumb]]]]
夏季某日，尼克收到蓋茨比宴會的邀請函。他在宴會上碰見喬丹·貝克，而且终于見到蓋茨比，发现盖茨比竟然在戰爭中與他同在一個師服役。尼克從喬丹那裏得知蓋茨比在1917年與黛西墜入愛河，但因为他要去参军，黛西最终嫁给了汤姆·布坎南。戰后，他赚了很多钱，在长岛买下豪宅，眺望海灣对面黛西的家，希望“再续前缘”。蓋茨比奢華的生活方式與放蕩的狂歡會不過是爲了吸引黛西，好讓她回心轉意。蓋茨比要尼克安排他與黛西見面。尼克邀請黛西到家品茶，隱瞞了蓋茨比到場一事。在一陣尴尬後，蓋茨比和黛西舊情復燃。他們再次相戀，而湯姆很快起了疑心。在某次飯局上，黛西對蓋茨比言辭甜蜜，毫不掩飾，湯姆的懷疑成真。雖然湯姆自己也有情婦，但他對妻子出軌倍感憤怒。湯姆逼迫大家前往紐約市，在[[廣場酒店|廣場酒店]]的套房裏與蓋茨比對質，告訴他夫妻间的故事是蓋茨比所不能領悟的。不僅如此，他揭露蓋茨比販賣[[私酒|私酒]]，從事其它見不得人的勾當，才得到了今日的财富。黛西感觉自己无法承受，只想离开，湯姆叫蓋茨比驱车送她回家。

尼克、喬丹、湯姆驅車回家时經過“灰燼谷”，發現湯姆的情婦默特爾被盖茨比的车撞死了。事後，尼克從蓋茨比那裏得知當時是黛西开车，但蓋茨比不愿揭发自己深爱的女人。默特爾的丈夫喬治以爲車主就是自己妻子外遇的對象，對此展開搜索。湯姆誤導喬治，後者發現車主是蓋茨比後，來到豪宅，開槍行凶，隨後自盡。尼克爲蓋茨比舉辦葬禮，結束了與喬丹的關係，看破了東部的生活方式，回到了中西部的老家。

=== 主要人物 ===
*'''[[尼克·卡拉威|尼克·卡拉威]]'''（Nick Carraway）<br/>  耶魯大學畢業生，來自中西部，一戰老兵。在故事開始時新搬到西卵居住，年齡29歲（後30歲）。他是小說的第一敘事人，是蓋茨比的鄰居、股票經紀。尼克性格隨和，有時言語諷刺，有些樂觀，但這些性格隨著劇情的發展逐漸淡化。
*'''{{link-en|傑·蓋茨比|Jay Gatsby}}'''（Jay Gatsby）<br/> 年輕、神秘的百萬富翁，有些商業背景（後被揭露是販賣私酒），來自[[北達科他州|北達科他州]]。他著迷于黛西·布坎南，倆人曾在一戰相戀。根據馬修·J·布拉克利<ref>Matthew J. Bruccoli</ref>對菲茨杰拉德的傳記《有些偉大的史詩》<ref>''Some Sort of Epic Grandeur''</ref>，人物形象是基于走私販子，一戰軍官麥克斯·格拉克（M. Gerlach）。據稱，一戰後蓋茨比曾經在英國[[牛津大学|牛津]][[牛津大学三一学院|三一學院]]短期進修<ref name=Oxford>{{cite book |last=McCullen |first=Bonnie Shannon |chapter=This Tremendous Detail: The Oxford Stone in the House of Gatsby |editor1-last=Assadi |editor1-first=Jamal |editor2-last=Freedman |editor2-first=William |publisher=New York: Peter Lang |year=2007 |title=A Distant Drummer: Foreign Perspectives on F. Scott Fitzgerald |isbn=978-0820488516}}</ref>
*'''{{link-en|黛西·布卡南|Daisy Buchanan}}'''（Daisy Buchanan）<br/>   魅力十足、充滿激情、膚淺、自戀的妙齡女子，被認爲是輕佻女郎。<ref>{{cite book |last=Conor |first=Liz |title=The Spectacular Modern Woman: Feminine Visibility in the 1920s |publisher=Indiana University Press |isbn=978-0-253-21670-0 |page=[http://books.google.com/books?id=jWG2_Pt2Dw8C&pg=PA301 301] |url=http://www.iupress.indiana.edu/product_info.php?products_id=21644 |accessdate=24 February 2013 |date=22 June 2004 |archive-date=2020-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224021222/http://www.iupress.indiana.edu/product_info.php?products_id=21644 |dead-url=no }}</ref>她是尼克的二堂妹，湯姆·布坎南的妻子。菲茨傑拉德與吉尼芙拉·金（Ginevra King）曾經有段風流史，被認爲是創作黛西的靈感。在嫁給湯姆前，黛西曾經與蓋茨比有過戀情。她對蓋茨比和湯姆之間的選擇是小說的主要矛盾之一。
*'''湯姆·布坎南'''（Thomas "Tom" Buchanan）<br/>   住在東卵的百萬富翁，黛西的丈夫。湯姆身材矯健，嗓音沙啞，傲慢自大，是耶魯大學的前橄榄球星。布坎南與威廉·米切爾類似，後者迎娶了吉尼芙拉·金。布坎南和米切爾都是喜愛打[[馬球|馬球]]的芝加哥人。菲茨傑拉德憎恨吉尼芙拉的父親，和他一樣，布坎南曾經在耶魯就讀，是個[[白人優越主義|白人優越主義者]]。<ref name=B911>{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2000|pp=9–11}}</ref>
*'''喬丹·貝克'''（Jordan Baker）<br/>   黛西·布坎南的老友，“秋葉黃”般的頭髮，運動員般的體格，態度高傲。在故事的絕大部分中，她是尼克的女友；業餘高爾夫球手，有些不誠實的壞名聲。菲茨傑拉德告訴麥克斯韋·帕金斯（M.Perkins）喬丹的形象是基于高爾夫球手伊迪斯·卡明斯（Edith Cummings），是吉尼芙拉·金的朋友。<ref name=B911/>她的名字來自于曾經流行的品牌喬丹汽車和貝克汽車<ref>Jordan Motor Car Company, Baker Motor Vehicle</ref>，影射喬丹“快捷”的名聲和美國人所代表的自由，特別是二十年代的女性。<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Bruccoli |editor-first=Matthew J. |editor-link=Matthew J. Bruccoli |last=Fitzgerald |first=F. Scott |authorlink=F. Scott Fitzgerald |title=The Great Gatsby |series=The Cambridge Edition of the Works of F. Scott Fitzgerald |year=1991 |publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=9780521402309 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ga07kW8soU8C&lpg=PA184&vq=baker%20electric&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q=baker%20electric&f=false |accessdate=6 July 2013 |page=184 |quote=This name combines two automobile makes: the sporty Jordan and the conservative Baker electric. |archive-date=2014-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102062800/http://books.google.com/books?id=ga07kW8soU8C&lpg=PA184&vq=baker%20electric&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q=baker%20electric&f=false |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Bloom |editor-first=Harold |editor-link=Harold Bloom |last=Fitzgerald |first=F. Scott |authorlink=F. Scott Fitzgerald |title=The Great Gatsby |year=2006 |publisher=Chelsea House Publishers |location=New York |isbn=9781438114545 |page=95 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=adjCx-wnhWsC&lpg=PA95&dq=great%20gatsby's%20romance%20of%20motoring%3A%20nick%20carraway%20and%20jordan%20baker&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q=10.%20mathew%20J.%20bruccoli&f=false |accessdate=6 July 2013 |archive-date=2014-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927115210/http://books.google.com/books?id=adjCx-wnhWsC&lpg=PA95&dq=great%20gatsby%27s%20romance%20of%20motoring%3A%20nick%20carraway%20and%20jordan%20baker&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q=10.%20mathew%20J.%20bruccoli&f=false |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Tredell |editor-first=Nicolas |last=Fitzgerald |first=F. Scott |authorlink=F. Scott Fitzgerald |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald: The Great Gatsby |series=Columbia Critical Guides |issn=1559-3002 |year=1997 |publisher=Columbia University Press |location=New York |isbn=9780231115353 |page=184 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=eEIfKVeIOEcC&lpg=PA184&ots=XEMCw7-MJe&dq=%22jordan%20baker%22%20baker%20electric&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q=%22jordan%20baker%22%20baker%20electric&f=false |accessdate=6 July 2013 |archive-date=2014-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927115228/http://books.google.com/books?id=eEIfKVeIOEcC&lpg=PA184&ots=XEMCw7-MJe&dq=%22jordan%20baker%22%20baker%20electric&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q=%22jordan%20baker%22%20baker%20electric&f=false |dead-url=no }}</ref>
*'''喬治·B·威爾遜'''（George B. Wilson）<br/>  修車廠主、技師。湯姆·布坎南和他的妻子默特爾·威爾遜都不喜歡他，稱他“笨得都不知道自己還活著。”當得知妻子遭遇不幸後，他誤認爲是蓋茨比所為，便下了毒手，隨後自殺。
*'''默特爾·威爾遜'''（Myrtle Wilson）<br/>  喬治的妻子，湯姆·布坎南的情婦。默特爾性格不安份，渴求逃出婚姻圍城，但爲此遭遇不幸。默特爾不巧撞上了蓋茨比的車（其實是黛西開車，但蓋茨比自願承擔了責任）。
*'''梅耶·沃爾夫西恩'''（Meyer Wolfshiem）{{refn|group=note|name=first|The spelling "Wolfshiem" appears throughout Fitzgerald's original manuscript, while "Wolfsheim" was introduced by an editor（[[Edmund_Wilson|Edmund Wilson]]）in the second edition<ref>{{cite book |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald: The Great Gatsby |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1991 |page=liv |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0yfauGsKOjAC&pg=PR54&lpg= |accessdate=2013-05-16 |archive-date=2014-01-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102113610/http://books.google.com/books?id=0yfauGsKOjAC&pg=PR54&lpg= |dead-url=no }}</ref> and appears in later Scribner's editions.<ref>{{cite book |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald: The Great Gatsby |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1991 |page=148 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ga07kW8soU8C&pg=PA148&lpg=wolfshiem+wolfsheim |accessdate=2013-05-16 |archive-date=2014-09-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140930191025/http://books.google.com/books?id=ga07kW8soU8C&pg=PA148&lpg=wolfshiem+wolfsheim |dead-url=no }}</ref>}}<br/>  猶太人，蓋茨比的導師，在[[世界大賽|棒球世界大賽]]上賭博。沃爾夫西恩在小說中僅出現兩次，拒絕參加蓋茨比的葬禮。他是對阿諾德·羅斯坦（A.Rothstein）的影射，後者是紐約罪犯頭目，被指責制造了黑襪醜聞，爲[[1919年世界大賽|1919年世界大賽]]抹了黑。<ref>{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2000|p=29}}</ref>

== 寫作與出版 ==
{{multiple image
| align = right
| direction = vertical
| width = 200
| image1 = Beacon Towers from the beach 1920.jpg
| alt1 = Beacon Towers
| caption1 = 已廢棄的{{link-en|比肯塔|Beacon Towers}}给蓋茨比豪宅帶來靈感
| image2 = Oheka Castle 0818b.JPG
| alt2 = Oheka Castle
| caption2 = 北岸[[奧赫卡城堡|奧赫卡城堡]]爲故事地點帶來靈感
}}
菲茨杰拉德在1922年開始計劃他的第三部小說，<ref name="Bruccoli 2000 53–54"/>但因爲他的戲劇《蔬菜》做編而拖延，耽擱了夏天和秋天。<ref>{{cite news |title=Gatsby, 35 Years Later |last=Mizener |first=Arthur |authorlink=Arthur Mizener |date=24 April 1960 |publisher=The New York Times |url=http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html |accessdate=29 July 2013 |quote=He had begun to plan the novel in June, 1923, saying to Maxwell Perkins, 'I want to write something new - something extraordinary and beautiful and simple and intricately patterned.' But that summer and fall was devoted to the production of his play, 'The Vegetable.' |archive-date=2018-01-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131072256/http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>戲劇演的一塌糊塗，菲茨杰拉德不得不花整個冬天爲雜志寫故事來還債。<ref>{{cite book |last=Curnutt |first=Kirk |title=A Historical Guide to F. Scott Fitzgerald |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=0195153030 |url=http://global.oup.com/academic/product/a-historical-guide-to-f-scott-fitzgerald-9780195153033?cc=us& |accessdate=11 October 2013 |page=58 |quote=The failure of ''The Vegetable'' in the fall of 1923 caused Fitzgerald, who was by then in considerable debt, to shut himself in a stuffy room over a garage in [[Great_Neck,_New_York|Great Neck, New York]], and write himself out of the red by turning out ten short stories for the magazine market.}}</ref><ref name=nyt35>{{cite news |last=Mizener |first=Arthur |authorlink=Arthur Mizener |title=Gatsby, 35 Years Later |date=24 April 1960 |publisher=''[[The_New_York_Times|The New York Times]]'' |url=http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html |accessdate=12 May 2013 |archive-date=2018-01-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131072256/http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>用他自己的話來說，這些故事“全都是垃圾，它幾乎讓我心碎，”<ref name=nyt35/>其中的一個故事叫做《冬天的夢》，後被菲茨杰拉德稱之爲“蓋茨比想法的第一份草稿”。<ref>{{cite book |last=Fitzgerald |first=F. Scott |authorlink=F. Scott Fitzgerald |editor-last=Turnbull |editor-first=Andrew |title=The Letters of F. Scott Fitzgerald |publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons |year=1963 |page=189 |quote=3. 'Winter Dreams' (a sort of first draft of the Gatsby idea from ''Metropolitan'' 1923)}}</ref>

在孩子出生之後，菲茨杰拉德于1922年10月移居長島大頸郡；該郡成爲《了不起的盖茨比》的背景。<ref>{{cite news |last=Murphy |first=Mary Jo |title=Eyeing the Unreal Estate of Gatsby Esq. |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/01/nyregion/01gatsby.html?scp=58&sq=f%20scott%20fitzgerald&st=cse |work=The New York Times |date=30 September 2010 |accessdate=2014-04-12 |archive-date=2020-02-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222173356/https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/01/nyregion/01gatsby.html?scp=58&sq=f%20scott%20fitzgerald&st=cse |dead-url=no }}</ref>菲茨傑拉德的鄰居是紐約新貴，如作家瑞恩·拉德納，演員盧·菲爾德，喜劇演員艾德·溫<ref>Writer Ring Lardner, actor Lew Fields, and comedian Ed Wynn</ref><ref name="Bruccoli 2000 53–54"/>。這些人物都是些“[[暴發戶|暴發戶]]”，不像來自曼哈西特灣或北岸的老財主。這些現實的並列給予菲茨杰拉德靈感，創作了“西卵”和“東卵”。在小說中，大頸是暴發戶，被稱之爲“西卵”；華盛頓港則是老財主，被稱之爲“東卵”。<ref>{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2000|pp=38–39}}</ref>幾座豪宅則爲蓋茨比家提供靈感，如奧卡城堡（Oheka Castle）<ref>{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2000|p=45}}</ref>和已廢棄的比肯塔（Beacon Towers）。<ref name=mansions>{{cite book |title=The Mansions of Long Island's Gold Coast |last=Randall |first=Mónica |year=2003 |publisher=Rizzoli |isbn=978-0-8478-2649-0 |pages=275–277}}</ref>

到了1923年中，菲茨杰拉德已經寫了18,000字<ref>{{cite book |last=West |first=James L. W., III |others=Cover Design by Dennis M. Arnold |title=Trimalchio: An Early Version of ''The Great Gatsby'' |year=2000 |series=The Cambridge Edition of the Works of F. Scott Fitzgerald |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-89047-0 |url=http://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/literature/american-literature/f-scott-fitzgerald-trimalchio-early-version-great-gatsby |accessdate=27 July 2013 |page=xi |quote=He produces 18,000 words; most of this material is later discarded, but he salvages the short story "Absolution," published in June 1924. |archive-date=2020-02-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222173412/https://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/literature/american-literature/f-scott-fitzgerald-trimalchio-early-version-great-gatsby |dead-url=no }}</ref>，但刪去了絕大部分，這些在1924年重新出現在短篇小說《寬恕》當中。<ref name="Bruccoli 2000 53–54"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2013/05/07/absolution_and_great_gatsby_f_scott_fitzgerald_story_gives_us_gatsby_as.html |title=The Forgotten Childhood of Jay Gatsby |first=David |last=Haglund |date=7 May 2013 |publisher=[[Slate_(magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=2014-04-12 |archive-date=2018-09-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922023707/http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2013/05/07/absolution_and_great_gatsby_f_scott_fitzgerald_story_gives_us_gatsby_as.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>

菲茨杰拉德在1924年開始專心寫作，他告訴自己的記賬人“總算從樹林裏出來，開始寫作了。”<ref name=nyt35/>他決定抛開之前的故事，告訴帕金斯小說是“有意識的藝術成就”<ref>{{cite journal |last=Eble |first=Kenneth |title=The Great Gatsby |journal=College Literature |issn=00933139 |date=Winter 1974 |volume=1 |issue=1 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/25111007 |accessdate=24 May 2013 |page=37 |quote=consciously artistic achievement |archive-date=2021-01-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112234843/https://www.jstor.org/stable/25111007 |dead-url=no }}</ref>，“純粹的創作 —不是我編的垃圾幻想故事，而是對真摯光明世界的持續思考。”<ref>{{cite news |last=Flanagan |first=Thomas |title=Fitzgerald's 'Radiant World' |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2000/dec/21/fitzgeralds-radiant-world/?pagination=false |accessdate=24 May 2013 |newspaper=The New York Review of Books |date=21 December 2000 |quote=He may have been remembering Fitzgerald's words in that April letter: ''So in my new novel I'm thrown directly on purely creative work—not trashy imaginings as in my stories but the sustained imagination of a sincere yet radiant world.'' |archive-date=2015-09-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909093725/http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2000/dec/21/fitzgeralds-radiant-world/?pagination=false |dead-url=no }}</ref>之後，在編訂過程中，他補充道，自己感覺“有種巨大的力量在我身上，是我從未感受過的。”<ref>{{cite journal |last=Leader |first=Zachary |authorlink=Zachary Leader |title=Daisy packs her bags |journal=London Review of Books |date=21 September 2000 |volume=22 |issue=18 |pages=13–15 |url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v22/n18/zachary-leader/daisy-packs-her-bags |accessdate=24 February 2013 |issn=0260-9592 |archive-date=2019-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191206190115/https://www.lrb.co.uk/v22/n18/zachary-leader/daisy-packs-her-bags |dead-url=no }}</ref>但在靈感的爆發後不久，菲茨杰拉德一家搬到[[蔚藍海岸|蔚藍海岸]]，關係也遂即緊張起來。<ref name=nyt35/>然而，到了八月份，菲茨杰拉德努力工作，約在十月份完成了第一份手稿，于十月三十號送到編輯麥克斯韋·帕金斯和代理人哈羅德·奧伯（Harold Ober）手中。<ref name=nyt35/>一家人在冬天搬到了羅馬。<ref>{{cite book |last=Tate |first=Mary Jo |title=Critical Companion to F. Scott Fitzgerald: A Literary Reference to His Life and Work |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=C90C_Du_lKIC&lpg=PA326&ots=NzAmA5JiKh&dq=F.%20Scott%20Fitzgerald%2C%20%22The%20High%20Cost%20of%20Macaroni%22&pg=PA326#v=onepage&q=F.%20Scott%20Fitzgerald,%20%22The%20High%20Cost%20of%20Macaroni%22&f=false |accessdate=27 July 2013 |year=2007 |publisher=Infobase Publishing |isbn=9781438108452 |page=326 |quote=They lived in <tt>ROME</tt> from October 1924 to February 1925... |archive-date=2014-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140926041519/http://books.google.com/books?id=C90C_Du_lKIC&lpg=PA326&ots=NzAmA5JiKh&dq=F.%20Scott%20Fitzgerald%2C%20%22The%20High%20Cost%20of%20Macaroni%22&pg=PA326#v=onepage&q=F.%20Scott%20Fitzgerald,%20%22The%20High%20Cost%20of%20Macaroni%22&f=false |dead-url=no }}</ref>十一月，帕金斯寫信告訴他人物蓋茨比“有些模糊”，他的財富和商業需要“一些解釋”，應該進行“勾勒”，菲茨杰拉德便做了修改。<ref>{{cite book |last=Perkins |first=Maxwell Evarts |authorlink=Maxwell Perkins |editor1-last=Bruccoli |editor1-first=Matthew Joseph |editor1-link=Matthew Joseph Bruccoli |editor2-last=Baughman |editor2-first=Judith S. |title=The Sons of Maxwell Perkins: Letters of F. Scott Fitzgerald, Ernest Hemingway, Thomas Wolfe, and Their Editor |year=2004 |publisher=Univ. of South Carolina Press |isbn=9781570035487 |pages=27–30}}</ref>

經過幾輪修改後，菲茨杰拉德在1925年2月終于完成終稿。<ref>{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2000|pp=54–56}}</ref>他的修改包括對第六章和第八章。<ref name=nyt35/>雖然如此，他拒絕了連載版權的$10,000，以便趕得上圖書的出版。<ref name=nyt35/>他在1923年提前收到$3939，<ref>{{cite web |last=Fitzerald |first=F. Scott |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald's ledger |url=http://digital.tcl.sc.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/fitz/id/82/show/17/rec/2 |work=Irvin Department of Rare Books and Special Collections |publisher=University of South Carolina |accessdate=29 April 2013 |archive-date=2016-06-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604075901/http://digital.tcl.sc.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/fitz/id/82/show/17/rec/2 |dead-url=no }}</ref>在出版時收到$1981.25。<ref>{{cite web |last=Zuckerman |first=Esther |title=The Finances of F. Scott Fitzgerald, Handwritten by Fitzgerald |url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/entertainment/2013/04/finances-f-scott-fitzgerald-handwritten-fitzgerald/64673/ |work=The Atlantic Wire |publisher=[[The_Atlantic_Media_Company|The Atlantic Media Company]] |accessdate=29 April 2013 |archive-date=2013-11-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106011233/http://www.theatlanticwire.com/entertainment/2013/04/finances-f-scott-fitzgerald-handwritten-fitzgerald/64673/ |dead-url=no }}</ref>

== 封面插圖 ==
第一版《了不起的盖茨比》的封面插圖是美國文學最爲著名的作品之一。<ref name=scribner>{{cite journal |last=Scribner |first=Charles, III |authorlink=Charles Scribner III |date=Winter 1992 |title=Celestial Eyes: From Metamorphosis to Masterpiece |journal=Princeton University Library Chronicle |volume=53 |issue=2 |pages=140–155<!--The Chronicle index wrongly gives 141-156.--> |url=http://libweb5.princeton.edu/visual_materials/pulc/pulc_v_53_n_2.pdf |accessdate=27 July 2013 |author= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106010409/http://libweb5.princeton.edu/visual_materials/pulc/pulc_v_53_n_2.pdf |archive-date=2013-11-06 |dead-url=yes }}（originally published as a brochure on 24 October 1991 to celebrate the Cambridge Edition of ''The Great Gatsby''）</ref>它描繪了一雙空洞的眼睛和一張浮在藍天的嘴巴，折射出霓虹中的女郎。在菲茨杰拉德寫作時，默默無名的藝術家弗朗西斯·庫加特（F.Cugat）負責繪制<ref name=scribner/>插圖在小說完成前就準備妥當；菲茨杰拉德對此沈醉，告訴他的出版人自己“把它寫進了”自己的小說中。<ref name=scribner/>菲茨杰拉德稱插圖與小說的關係以虛構眼科醫生艾克爾堡大夫的形式出現，<ref>{{cite journal |last=Scribner |first=Charles, III |authorlink=Charles Scribner III |date=Winter 1992 |title=Celestial Eyes: From Metamorphosis to Masterpiece |journal=Princeton University Library Chronicle |volume=53 |issue=2 |pages=140–155<!--The Chronicle index wrongly gives 141-156.--> |url=http://libweb5.princeton.edu/visual_materials/pulc/pulc_v_53_n_2.pdf |accessdate=27 July 2013 |quote=We are left then with the enticing possibility that Fitzgerald's arresting image was originally prompted by Cugat's fantastic apparitions over the valley of ashes; in other words, that the author derived his inventive metamorphosis from a recurrent theme of Cugat's trial jackets, one which the artist himself was to reinterpret and transform through subsequent drafts. |author= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106010409/http://libweb5.princeton.edu/visual_materials/pulc/pulc_v_53_n_2.pdf |archive-date=2013-11-06 |dead-url=yes }}（originally published as a brochure on 24 October 1991 to celebrate the Cambridge Edition of ''The Great Gatsby''）</ref>（它出現在喬治·威爾遜修車廠上方破敗的廣告牌中）書中描寫道“藍色的，龐大無比——瞳仁就有一碼高。這雙眼睛不是從一張臉上向外看，而是從架在一個不存在的鼻子上的一副碩大無朋的黃色眼鏡向外看。{{refn|group=note|The original edition used the anatomically incorrect word "retinas", while some later editions have used the word "irises".}}”雖然這段話與插圖有些關係，更加細微的解釋可以從黛西·布坎南的描述中得到“女孩無神的面龐浮遊在黑暗的檐口和絢爛的信號當中。”<ref name=scribner/>[[海明威|海明威]]在《[[流動的饗宴|流動的饗宴]]》中寫道當菲茨杰拉德借給他一份《了不起的盖茨比》時，他立即對封面產生反感，但“斯科特告訴我別讓它分心，這是長島高速公路上的廣告牌，對小說十分重要。他說曾經挺喜歡護封，但現在不怎麽喜歡了。”<ref>{{cite book |title=[[A_Moveable_Feast|A Moveable Feast]] |last=Hemingway |first=Ernest |authorlink=Ernest Hemingway |year=1964 |publisher=[[Charles_Scribner's_Sons|Scribner]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-684-82499-4 |page=[https://archive.org/details/moveablefeast00hemi_mxe/page/176 176]}}</ref>

== 標題 ==
菲茨杰拉德在命名小說上犯了難，最後不得不將其命名爲《了不起的盖茨比》，<ref name=studio360>{{cite news |last=Anderson |first=Kurt |authorlink=Kurt Andersen |title=American Icons: The Great Gatsby |url=http://www.studio360.org/story/95326-american-icons-the-great-gatsby/ |accessdate=22 May 2013 |newspaper=Studio 360 |at=14:26 |date=25 November 2010 |quote=[Donald Skemer（introduced 12:59）speaking] He went through many many titles, uh, including ''Under the Red, White, and Blue'' and ''Trimalchio'' and ''Gold-hatted Gatsby'' ... [James West（introduced at 12:11）speaking] ''The High Bouncing Lover''. And, uh, he in the end didn't think that ''The Great Gatsby'' was a very good title, was dissatisfied with it. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013015807/http://www.studio360.org/story/95326-american-icons-the-great-gatsby/ |archivedate=2013年10月13日 }}</ref>這一命名從亚伦-福尼尔的《了不起的米尔纳斯》<ref>Alain-Fournier's ''Le Grand Meaulnes''</ref>得到靈感。<ref>{{cite journal |last= |first= |title=The girl at the Grand Palais |journal=The Economist |date=22 December 2012 |url=http://www.economist.com/news/christmas/21568581-adolescent-obsession-inspired-influential-yet-neglected-french-classic-girl |accessdate=27 March 2013 |archive-date=2018-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401075146/https://www.economist.com/news/christmas/21568581-adolescent-obsession-inspired-influential-yet-neglected-french-classic-girl |dead-url=no }}</ref>在此之前，菲茨杰拉德嘗試使用過許多標題<ref>''Gatsby''; ''Among Ash-Heaps and Millionaires''; ''Trimalchio''; ''Trimalchio in West Egg''; ''On the Road to West Egg''; ''Under the Red, White, and Blue''; ''Gold-Hatted Gatsby''; ''The High-Bouncing Lover''。</ref><ref name=vanderbilt>{{cite book |last=Vanderbilt |first=Arthur T. |title=The Making of a Bestseller: From Author to Reader |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=54qLAaxz19wC&lpg=PA96&dq=I%20have%20now%20decided%20to%20stick%20to%20the%20title%20I%20put%20on%20the%20book&pg=PA96#v=onepage&q=I%20have%20now%20decided%20to%20stick%20to%20the%20title%20I%20put%20on%20the%20book&f=false |accessdate=27 July 2013 |year=1999 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=0786406631 |page=96 |quote=A week later, in his next letter, he was floundering: 'I have not decided to stick to the title I put on the book, ''Trimalchio in West Egg''. The only other titles that seem to fit it are ''Trimalchio'' and ''On the Road to West Egg''. I had two others, ''Gold-hatted Gatsby'' and ''The High-bouncing Lover'', but they seemed too slight.' |archive-date=2014-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140926035931/http://books.google.com/books?id=54qLAaxz19wC&lpg=PA96&dq=I%20have%20now%20decided%20to%20stick%20to%20the%20title%20I%20put%20on%20the%20book&pg=PA96#v=onepage&q=I%20have%20now%20decided%20to%20stick%20to%20the%20title%20I%20put%20on%20the%20book&f=false |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref name=studio360/>他最初給出的命名是''Trimalchio''（特立馬喬），他是彼得羅紐斯《酒色之徒》中一名殘忍的[[暴發戶|暴發戶]]，甚至曾經將蓋茨比與特立馬喬做了比較：“有趣的是，某一個星期六晚上，當蓋茨比在巅峰時，屋子裏的燈突然滅掉了——正如這昏暗降臨一樣，他特立馬喬般的事業也結束了。”<ref>F. Scott Fitzgerald, Chapter 7 opening sentence, ''The Great Gatsby''</ref>與蓋茨比奢華的宴會不同，特立馬喬組織的狂歡更加放肆、淫蕩，根據托尼·塔納（T.Tanner）企鵝版的序言，兩者之間的關係十分微妙。<ref>Tanner's introduction to the [[Penguin_Books|Penguin]] edition (2000), p. vii–viii.</ref>

1924年11月，菲茨杰拉德寫給帕金斯說“我現在決定使用書上的標題 ...《西卵的特拉馬喬》”，<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hill |first1=W. Speed |last2=Burns |first2=Edward M. |last3=Shillingsburg |first3=Peter L. |title=Text: An Interdisciplinary Annual of Textual Studies |volume=14 |year=2002 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |isbn=0472112724 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Wk2IacD_t8YC&lpg=PA331&ots=UDbwY0v0am&dq=%22I%20have%20now%20decided%20to%20stick%20to%20the%20title%20I%20put%20on%20the%20book%22&pg=PA331#v=onepage&q=%22I%20have%20now%20decided%20to%20stick%20to%20the%20title%20I%20put%20on%20the%20book%22&f=false |quote=..., because in early November he wrote Perkins that "I have now decided to stick to the title I put on the book. ''Trimalchio in West Egg.'' |access-date=2014-04-15 |archive-date=2014-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140926040259/http://books.google.com/books?id=Wk2IacD_t8YC&lpg=PA331&ots=UDbwY0v0am&dq=%22I%20have%20now%20decided%20to%20stick%20to%20the%20title%20I%20put%20on%20the%20book%22&pg=PA331#v=onepage&q=%22I%20have%20now%20decided%20to%20stick%20to%20the%20title%20I%20put%20on%20the%20book%22&f=false |dead-url=no }}</ref>但因引述十分晦澀，難以理解而最終放棄。<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fitzgerald |first1=Francis Scott |authorlink1=F. Scott Fitzgerald |last2=Perkins |first2=Maxwell |authorlink2=Maxwell Perkins |editor1-last=Kuehl |editor1-first=John |editor2-last=Bryer |editor2-first=Jackson R. |title=Dear Scott/Dear Max: the Fitzgerald-Perkins correspondence |year=1971 |publisher=Macmillan Publishing Company |page=87 |quote=When [[Ring_Lardner|Ring Lardner]] came in the other day I told him about your novel and he instantly balked at the title. 'No one could pronounce it,' he said; so probably your change is wise on other than typographical counts.}}</ref>他的妻子塞爾達和帕金斯都推薦《了不起的盖茨比》，菲茨杰拉德在一個月後終于表示同意。<ref>{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2002|pp=206–07}}</ref>在出版前的一個月最後的一輪校對中，他問是否可以將小說重新命名爲《特立馬喬》或是《金冒蓋茨比》，但帕金斯表示堅決反對。1925年3月19日，<ref>{{cite book |last=Tate |first=Mary Jo |title=Critical Companion to F. Scott Fitzgerald: A Literary Reference to His Life and Work |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=C90C_Du_lKIC&lpg=PA87&dq=CRAZY%20ABOUT%20TITLE%20UNDER%20THE%20RED%20WHITE%20AND%20BLUE%20STOP%20WHAT%20WOULD%20DELAY%20BE&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q=CRAZY%20ABOUT%20TITLE%20UNDER%20THE%20RED%20WHITE%20AND%20BLUE%20STOP%20WHAT%20WOULD%20DELAY%20BE&f=false |accessdate=27 July 2013 |year=2007 |publisher=Infobase Publishing |isbn=9781438108452 |page=87 |quote=He settled on ''The Great Gatsby'' in December 1924, but in January and March 1925 he continued to express his concern to Perkins about the title, cabling from <tt>CAPRI</tt> on March 19: '<tt>CRAZY ABOUT TITLE UNDER THE RED WHITE AND BLUE STOP {{sic|WHART}} WOULD DELAY BE</tt>' |archive-date=2014-09-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140930101951/http://books.google.com/books?id=C90C_Du_lKIC&lpg=PA87&dq=CRAZY%20ABOUT%20TITLE%20UNDER%20THE%20RED%20WHITE%20AND%20BLUE%20STOP%20WHAT%20WOULD%20DELAY%20BE&pg=PA87#v=onepage&q=CRAZY%20ABOUT%20TITLE%20UNDER%20THE%20RED%20WHITE%20AND%20BLUE%20STOP%20WHAT%20WOULD%20DELAY%20BE&f=false |dead-url=no }}</ref>菲茨杰拉德提議是否可以將小說改名爲《在紅、白、藍下》，但此時已經沒有時間了。<ref>{{cite web |last=Lipton |first=Gabrielle |title=Where Is Jay Gatsby's Mansion? |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/culturebox/2013/05/where_is_the_real_jay_gatsby_mansion_from_f_scott_fitzgerald_s_the_great.html |work=slate.com |publisher=The Slate Group, a Division of the Washington Post Company |accessdate=6 May 2013 |quote=However, nearing the time of publication, Fitzgerald, who despised the title ''The Great Gatsby'' and toiled for months to think of something else, wrote to Perkins that he had finally found one: ''Under the Red, White, and Blue''. Unfortunately, it was too late to change. |archive-date=2021-01-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111075914/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/culturebox/2013/05/where_is_the_real_jay_gatsby_mansion_from_f_scott_fitzgerald_s_the_great.html |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Churchwell |first=Sarah |authorlink=Sarah Churchwell |title=What makes The Great Gatsby great? |date=3 May 2013 |publisher=The Guardian |url=http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/03/what-makes-great-gatsby?CMP=twt_gu&CMP=NECNETTXT766 |accessdate=11 October 2013 |quote=At the last minute, he had asked his editor if they could change the new novel's title to ''Under the Red, White and Blue'', but it was too late. |archive-date=2020-09-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200914221438/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/03/what-makes-great-gatsby?CMP=twt_gu&CMP=NECNETTXT766 |dead-url=no }}</ref>1925年4月10日，《了不起的蓋茨比》終于面世。<ref>{{cite book |last=Lazo |first=Caroline Evensen |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald: Voice of the Jazz Age |url=https://archive.org/details/fscottfitzgerald00lazo |year=2003 |publisher=Twenty-First Century Books |isbn=0822500744 |page=[https://archive.org/details/fscottfitzgerald00lazo/page/75 75] |quote=When the book was published on April 10, 1924, the critics raved.}}</ref>菲茨杰拉德覺得“題目還湊合，說不上好。”<ref>{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2002|pp=215–17}}</ref>

早期草稿的題目是《特立馬喬：了不起的盖茨比的一個早期版本》<ref>''Trimalchio: An Early Version of The Great Gatsby''</ref>，草稿後被出版。<ref>{{cite book |last=West |first=James L. W., III |others=Cover Design by Dennis M. Arnold |title=Trimalchio: An Early Version of ''The Great Gatsby'' |year=2000 |series=The Cambridge Edition of the Works of F. Scott Fitzgerald |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-89047-0 |url=http://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/literature/american-literature/f-scott-fitzgerald-trimalchio-early-version-great-gatsby |accessdate=27 July 2013 |archive-date=2020-02-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222173412/https://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/literature/american-literature/f-scott-fitzgerald-trimalchio-early-version-great-gatsby |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/james-l-w-west-iii/what-baz-luhrmann-asked-m_b_3047387.html |title=What Baz Luhrmann Asked Me About ''The Great Gatsby'' |last=West |first=James L. W., III |date=10 April 2013 |work=The Huffington Post |accessdate=27 July 2013 |quote=Luhrmann was also interested in ''Trimalchio'', the early version of ''The Great Gatsby'' that I published in 2000 as a volume in the Cambridge Edition. |archive-date=2017-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024120507/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/james-l-w-west-iii/what-baz-luhrmann-asked-m_b_3047387.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>兩份草稿有明顯差異，但從中看來，草稿並非完全失敗。另一個差異是湯姆·布坎南和蓋茨比之間的爭辯更加平和，<ref>{{cite web |last=Alter |first=Alexandra |title=A Darker, More Ruthless Gatsby |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=11 July 2013 |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324030704578426990802631684.html#articleTabs=article |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002164028/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324030704578426990802631684.html#articleTabs=article |archivedate=2013-10-02 |date=19 April 2013 |quote=Gatsby comes across as more confident and aggressive in 'Trimalchio' during a confrontation with romantic rival Tom Buchanan at the Plaza Hotel, challenging Tom's assertion that Gatsby and Daisy's affair is 'a harmless little flirtation.' |dead-url=yes }}</ref>雖然黛西最終回到湯姆身邊。

== 主題 ==
薩拉·徹奇維爾（S.Churchwell）認爲《了不起的盖茨比》是“美國夢頹廢消極面的警世通言。”小說探討了人們對從頭再來的渴望、社會政治、殘忍以及對理想和人們的背叛。小說應用了反語和悲劇性結尾，深入剖析驕奢淫逸的主題和青春的莽撞毛糙。<ref>{{cite news |last=Churchwell |first=Sarah |authorlink=Sarah Churchwell |title=What makes The Great Gatsby great? |date=3 May 2013 |publisher=The Guardian |url=http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/03/what-makes-great-gatsby?CMP=twt_gu&CMP=NECNETTXT766 |accessdate=11 October 2013 |archive-date=2020-09-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200914221438/https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/03/what-makes-great-gatsby?CMP=twt_gu&CMP=NECNETTXT766 |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref name=boston/>

其它人，如記者尼克·吉萊斯皮（N.Gillespie）認爲《了不起的盖茨比》揭示了“現代經濟不是以身份和繼承爲基礎，而是以創新和滿足消費者需求的能力來界定的，這使得階級劃分被打破。”<ref name=gillespie>{{cite news |last=Gillespie |first=Nick |authorlink=Nick Gillespie |title=The Great Gatsby's Creative Destruction |publisher=Reason |date=2 May 2013 |url=http://reason.com/archives/2013/05/02/the-great-gatsbys-creative-destruction/print |accessdate=12 May 2013 |archive-date=2018-06-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619140518/http://reason.com/archives/2013/05/02/the-great-gatsbys-creative-destruction/print |dead-url=no }}</ref>這種解釋主張《了不起的盖茨比》捕捉到了美國特色，因爲這是有關變革和阻撓的故事；有的變革來自新一波移民（二十世紀早期的南歐人、今天的拉美人），[[暴發戶|暴發戶]]，或少數民族的成功人士。美國從二十年代至今經歷過多次經濟和社會變革。正如吉萊斯皮所述“具體公式始終在改變著，從《蓋茨比》可以很容易得到共鳴，老牌經濟文化與新興力量是基本衝突，存在于美國社會的方方面面。”<ref name=gillespie/>由于這種觀念頗具美國特色，貫穿整個美國歷史，讀者是可以從《了不起的盖茨比》中細細品味的（也是小說經久不衰的原因）。<ref name=gillespie/>

== 反響 ==
1925年4月10日，《了不起的盖茨比》由斯克裏布納之子公司出版。當天，菲茨杰拉德致電帕金斯問詢情況：“有什麽消息嗎？”<ref name=nyt35/>20日，帕金斯回複“賣的不怎麽樣，但評價頗高。”菲茨杰拉德在4月24日回複稱消息令他“鬱悶”，結尾是“致您的，十分鬱悶。”<ref name=lc/>菲茨杰拉德希望小說會在商業上大獲成功，賣出75,000本。<ref name=lc>{{cite book |last=O'Meara |first=Lauraleigh |title=Lost City: Fitzgerald's New York |year=2002 |edition=1st paperback |isbn=978-0-415-86701-6 |publisher=Routledge |url=http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415940559/ |accessdate=21 May 2013 |archive-date=2014-12-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208102412/http://www.routledge.com/books/details/9780415940559/ |dead-url=no }}</ref>到了10月，當面世火熱過後，小說還沒賣到20,000本。<ref name=nyt35/><ref name=boston>{{cite news |title='Gatsby': What's so great? |last=Symkus |first=Ed |url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2013/05/04/gatsby-what-great/jiqRfty6ySLbZUXpXWf3sL/story.html |publisher=Boston Globe |date=4 May 2013 |accessdate=5 May 2013 |archive-date=2020-09-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200930055243/https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2013/05/04/gatsby-what-great/jiqRfty6ySLbZUXpXWf3sL/story.html |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref name=lc/>雖然如此，斯克裏布納持續著印刷；原始版一直用到1946年，此後，《蓋茨比》有了三個版本，原始版也就不再需要了。<ref name=nyt35/>菲茨杰拉德從同時代作家T. S.艾略特，伊迪斯·華頓、威拉·卡瑟那裏得到好評；然而，這都是私下的意見，菲茨杰拉德則瘋狂地希望獲得評論界和讀者的承認。<ref name=nyt35/>

在當時，評論界對《了不起的盖茨比》意見不一。《紐約時報》的艾德文·克拉克對小說的贊美溢于言表，認爲小說是個“有趣的故事，是當今神秘的、絢爛的故事。”<ref name=nytreview>{{cite news |last=Clark |first=Edwin |title=Scott Fitzgerald Looks Into Middle Age |date=19 April 1925 |publisher=''[[The_New_York_Times|The New York Times]]'' |url=http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby.html |accessdate=11 May 2013 |archive-date=2018-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180304084122/http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>同樣地，《洛杉矶時報》的莉莉安·C·福特寫到：“小說給讀者留下奇妙的經歷，回味無窮。”，稱小說“對生活的啓示”“一部藝術品。”<ref name=latreview>{{cite news |last=Ford |first=Lillian C. |title=The Seamy Side of Society |date=10 May 1925 |publisher=''[[Los_Angeles_Times|Los Angeles Times]]'' |url=http://www.latimes.com/features/books/jacketcopy/la-et-jc-great-gatsby-review-book-1925-20130506,0,3860329.story |accessdate=11 May 2013 |archive-date=2013-10-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027214319/http://www.latimes.com/features/books/jacketcopy/la-et-jc-great-gatsby-review-book-1925-20130506,0,3860329.story |dead-url=no }}</ref>《紐約郵報》稱小說“令人陶醉 …他的風格煥發才智，才華橫溢；他的寫作真摯酣暢。”<ref name=nypreview>{{cite news |title=Books On Our Table |author= |publisher=''[[The_New_York_Post|The New York Post]]'' |date=5 May 1925}}</ref>《紐約先驅者論壇》對小說不以爲然，認爲《了不起的盖茨比》不過是“純粹的暫時現象，當下妳所能想象的一些細微洞察它有所包含——很輕盈、很細致、很尖銳 ….是文學的檸檬糕點。”<ref name=nyhtreview>{{cite news |title=Turns with a Bookworm |author= |publisher=''[[New_York_Herald_Tribune|New York Herald Tribune]]'' |date=12 April 1925}}</ref>《芝加哥論壇報》的H.L.門肯稱小說“從形式上看不過是華美的轶事，而且可能還不是”，但贊揚小說“結局謹慎而絕妙。”<ref name=ctreview>{{cite news |last=Mencken |first=H. L. |authorlink=H·L·孟肯 |title=Scott Fitzgerald and His Work |publisher=''[[Chicago_Tribune|The Chicago Daily Tribune]]'' |date=3 May 1925}}</ref>

有些作者覺得較之先前作品，小說令人意猶未盡，隨即對此加以批評。《達拉斯早報》的哈維·伊格爾頓認爲小說標志著菲茨杰拉德成功的終結：“當讀完《了不起的盖茨比》後，人們感到遺憾，不是爲書中人物的命運，而是爲菲茨杰拉德先生。”<ref name=dmnreview>{{cite news |last=Eagleton |first=Harvey |title=Profits of the New Age III. F. Scott Fitzgerald |publisher=''[[The_Dallas_Morning_News|The Dallas Morning News]]'' |date=10 May 1925}}</ref>《皮卡有恩時報》的約翰·麥克盧爾認爲小說不可信，寫到“從概念和結構來看，《了不起的盖茨比》似乎有些生硬。”<ref name=tpreview>{{cite news |last=McClure |first=John |title=Literature-And Less |publisher=''[[The_Times-Picayune|The Times-Picayune]]'' |date=31 May 1925}}</ref>《聖路易斯郵報》的拉爾夫·科格倫覺得小說不如先前的作品好，認爲故事是個“次要演出 …此時的作者似乎有些無聊、疲倦、不忿。”<ref name=slpdreview>{{cite news |last=Coghlan |first=Ralph |title=F. Scott Fitzgerald |publisher=''[[St._Louis_Post-Dispatch|St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' |date=25 April 1925}}</ref>《紐約世界晚報》的露絲·斯奈德認爲故事的風格“痛苦強迫”，認爲編輯“在閱讀完《了不起的盖茨比》後確信菲茨杰拉德先生不是當今最偉大的美國作家之一。”<ref name=nyewreview>{{cite news |last=Snyder |first=Ruth |title=A Minute or Two with Books-F. Scott Fitzgerald Ventures |publisher=''[[New_York_World|New York Evening World]]'' |date=15 April 1925}}</ref>評論攻擊道菲茨杰拉德沒說到點上：“所有的評論，甚至是最富熱情的，都不知道故事所云。”<ref name=nyt35/>

菲茨杰拉德的目標是創作一篇文學作品，證明自己是個真正的作家，<ref name="Mizener 1951 167">{{Harvnb|Mizener|1951|p=167}}</ref>《了不起的盖茨比》在商業上沒有他之前的作品《人間天堂》和《美麗與毀滅》成功。雖然小說印刷了兩次，有些存貨多年賣不出去。<ref name="Bruccoli 2000 175">{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2000|p=175}}</ref>菲茨杰拉德自己將萎靡的銷路歸結爲時下的讀者群主要是女性，而《蓋茨比》中沒有一個像樣的姑娘。<ref name="Bruccoli 2000 175"/>根據他的帳薄，如今可以從[[南卡羅來納大學|南卡羅來納大學]]托馬斯·庫珀圖書館那裏看到，他從小說上僅獲利$2,000。<ref>{{cite news |last=Howell |first=Peter |title=Five things you didn't know about The Great Gatsby |url=http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2013/05/05/five_things_you_didnt_know_about_the_great_gatsby.html |work=The Star |date=5 May 2013 |accessdate=5 May 2013 |archive-date=2021-01-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112093627/https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/movies/2013/05/05/five_things_you_didnt_know_about_the_great_gatsby.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>雖然1926年歐文·戴維斯將其改編爲電影，[[派拉蒙電影|派拉蒙電影]]出了它的無聲版，都爲作者獲了利，但菲茨杰拉德依然覺得他沒有獲得應有的承認，覺得在成爲公衆嚴肅作家的問題上被潑了冷水。<ref name=nyt35/>有很多年，大衆認爲《了不起的盖茨比》不過在懷舊罷了。<ref name=nyt35/>

== 影響與現代分析 ==
[[File:F._Scott_and_Zelda_Fitzgerald_grave.png|200px]]的[[F·斯科特·菲茨杰拉德|菲茨杰拉德]]夫妇墓碑，其中墓志铭来自本书]]
1940年，菲茨杰拉德犯了第四次、也是最後一次心臟病，在離世時認爲自己的作品已經被人抛棄。在彌留之際，他寫給自己的女兒“現在，我希望自己從來沒有放松或是回首——但是正如在《了不起的盖茨比》最後所說的那樣：我找到了自己的方法——從現在起這是首要的。這是我當下的任務——除此以外我一無是處。”<ref name=nyt35/>但依照他來看，自己是個失敗者，在臨終前才賣出25,000本書。<ref name=usatodaysales>{{cite news|last=Donahue|first=Deirdre|title=''The Great Gatsby'' by the numbers|date=7 May 2013|work=[[USA_Today|USA Today]]|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2013/05/07/the-great-gatsby-is-a-bestseller-this-week/2133269/|accessdate=12 May 2013|archive-date=2017-08-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812122531/https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2013/05/07/the-great-gatsby-is-a-bestseller-this-week/2133269/|dead-url=no}}</ref>他在《紐約時報》上的訃告所引述的蓋茨比證明小說的潛力還遠沒有被挖掘出來。<ref>{{cite news|title=Scott Fitzgerald, Author, Dies at 44|date=23 December 1940|publisher=Nytimes.com|url=http://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0924.html|accessdate=30 August 2010|quote=The promise of his brilliant career was never fulfilled.|archive-date=2017-06-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606010739/http://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0924.html|dead-url=no}}</ref>然而，小說在背地裏卻頗受賞識；愛德華·紐豪斯和巴德·舒爾伯格深受小說影響，約翰·奧哈拉也是。<ref name=mizener2>{{cite news|last=Mizener|first=Arthur|authorlink=Arthur Mizener|title=Gatsby, 35 Years Later|url=http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html|publisher=''[[The_New_York_Times|The New York Times]]''|date=24 April 1960|accessdate=12 May 2013|quote=Writers like John O'Hara were showing its influence and younger men like Edward Newhouse and Budd Schulberg, who would presently be deeply affected by it, were discovering it.|archive-date=2018-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131072256/http://www.nytimes.com/books/00/12/24/specials/fitzgerald-gatsby60.html|dead-url=no}}</ref>1941年，愛德蒙·威爾遜在《最後的大亨》裏再版了《蓋茨比》，一時評論四起，絕大多數觀點認爲小說是個經久不衰的名著。<ref name=nyt35/>

1942年，一群出版人創辦了“戰時書會”（Council on Books in Wartime）。書會旨在爲參加二戰士兵發放圖書。《了不起的盖茨比》也在其中。小說在士兵中大受歡迎，根據《周六晚郵報》的評論，小說和“[[海報女郎|海報女郎]]有一拼”。<ref>{{cite news|last=Wittels|first=David|title=What the G.I. Reads|newspaper=The Saturday Evening Post|date=23 June 1945}}</ref>，共有155,000本《蓋茨比》送出海外，發放到戰士們手中，<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Cole|editor-first=John Y.|title=Books in Action: the Armed Services Editions|year=1984|publisher=Library of Congress|location=Washington|isbn=0844404667|url=http://catdir.loc.gov/catdir/toc/becites/cfb/84600198.html|accessdate=22 May 2013|page=28|quote=One hundred fifty-five thousand ASE copies of The Great Gatsby were distributed-as against the twenty-five thousand copies of the novel printed by Scribners between 1925 and 1942.|archive-date=2020-10-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201019003511/http://catdir.loc.gov/catdir/toc/becites/cfb/84600198.html|dead-url=no}}</ref>這最終導致了小說的出名和暢銷。<ref>{{cite news|last=Beckwith|first=Ryan Teague|title=A novel fact: Wartime - and the U.S. military - boosted sales of 'The Great Gatsby' from good to 'Great'|url=http://www.denverpost.com/entertainment/ci_23210783/from-good-sales-great-wartime-boosted-gatsby|accessdate=22 May 2013|newspaper=The Denver Post|date=12 May 2013|archive-date=2016-03-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304083913/http://www.denverpost.com/entertainment/ci_23210783/from-good-sales-great-wartime-boosted-gatsby|dead-url=no}}</ref>

到了1944年，對菲茨杰拉德作品的完整文獻出版，第二年，“有關《蓋茨比》不過是時下作品的觀點煙消雲散。”<ref name=nyt35/>在1945年，菲茨杰拉德的作品再此受到關注，二戰軍隊版《蓋茨比》有150,000本送到戰士手中，獲得了大量讀者群。<ref name="Bruccoli 2000 217">{{Harvnb|Bruccoli|2000|p=217}}</ref>在五十年代，小說逐漸成爲高中教科書，列爲必讀。<ref name=boston/>評論家愛德蒙·威爾遜是菲茨杰拉德的朋友，他爲這種複興做了鋪墊<ref>{{cite news|title=Careless people of F Scott Fitzgerald's Great Gatsby have a modern equivalent|last=Verghis|first=Sharon|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/careless-people-of-f-scott-fitzgeralds-great-gatsby-have-a-modern-equivalent/story-fn9n8gph-1226633866573|work=The Australian|date=4 May 2013|accessdate=5 May 2013|archive-date=2015-02-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209053435/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/careless-people-of-f-scott-fitzgeralds-great-gatsby-have-a-modern-equivalent/story-fn9n8gph-1226633866573|dead-url=no}}</ref>1951年，亞瑟·麥茲納寫的傳記《天堂的那邊》，描述這位天才作家甘苦的一生和悲劇的下場。<ref name="Bruccoli 2000 217"/>他強調了文學評論家對小說的積極評價，公衆對小說的態度，以及對作品的重新發現。<ref>{{Harvnb|Mizener|1951|p=183}}</ref>

到了1960年，小說每年都能賣出50,000本，《紐約時報》社論家亞瑟·麥茲納稱贊小說是“二十世紀美國名著。”<ref name=nyt35/>《了不起的盖茨比》在全球範圍內售出超過兩千五百萬本。<ref name=usatodaysales/>小說每年賣出500,000本，斯克裏布納之子公司的最爲著名；在2013年，僅電子書一版就賣出185,000本。<ref name=usatodaysales/>

中文版譯者[[喬志高|喬志高]]說“費滋傑羅幾乎成為美國文壇的icon（偶像），他的作品被稱為canon（經典），《大亨小傳》中的人物、情節、和語言，不時被人引用，好像這部書是個美國的allegory（寓言）”。[[村上春树|村上春树]]也对《了不起的盖茨比》由衷热爱，对其反复读过多遍。评价《了不起的盖茨比》美得无以复加，而且完美无缺，其文体简洁明快，又有自然之美。且村上先生着手于《了不起的盖茨比》的翻译工作，表示翻译一本书，意味着精心吟味书中所写的一字一句，换言之就是长期深入地介入整部作品（比喻为男女关系，也许接近多年共同起居的感觉），所以多有某种作用波及作品与自己的关系，但就《了不起的盖茨比》而言，根本不曾出现这样的情况。不论多么紧密地贴近，这部作品给我的印象也没有丝毫变化。“说来就是，《了不起的盖茨比》是一位才华横溢的青年在巅峰状态几乎一气呵成写出的‘朱庇特’（指《朱庇特交响曲》，莫扎特写于1788年的最后一部交响曲，被誉为其音乐创作的顶峰）式的作品（他自然是殚精竭虑写就的，但我还是认为不妨这么说）。”

== 名句 ==
{{Cquote|''"Whenever you feel like criticizing any one," he told me, "just remember that all the people in this world haven't had the advantages that you've had."''<br />'''他跟我說：“每當你想批評人的時候，要記得，世上不是所有人都像你一樣擁有許多優勢。”'''}}<ref name="汪芃">{{cit法蘭西斯·史考特·凱·費茲杰羅|title=《大亨小傳》|year=2012年|publisher=[[遠流出版事業股份有限公司|遠流出版事業股份有限公司]]|location=臺北市南昌路2段81號6樓|isbn=978-957-32-7013-3|authorlink=法蘭西斯·史考特·凱·費茲杰羅|editor=總編輯：汪若蘭;主編：陳希林；編輯：徐立妍|Others=[[黃子欽|黃子欽]]|edition=2012年9月1日初版一刷|series=經典文學新譯|language=zh-hant}}</ref>{{Rp|21}}

{{Cquote|''So we beat on, boats against the current, borne back ceaselessly into the past.''<br />'''我們便這樣揚著船帆迂迴前進，逆水行舟，而浪潮奔流不歇，又不停地將我們推向過去。'''}}<ref name="汪芃" />{{Rp|279}}

==改編作品==
《大亨小傳》曾多次被改編成不同表演格式的作品，包括[[電影|電影]]及[[歌剧|歌剧]]。

=== 電影與電視劇 ===
*《[[大亨小傳_(1926年電影)|大亨小傳]]》（1926年），導演是{{link-en|赫伯·佈雷農|Herbert Brenon}}——《大亨小傳》在出版一年後就被搬上銀幕。該片是[[無聲電影|無聲]][[黑白|黑白]]電影，主演有[[華納·巴士達|華納·巴士達]]、{{link-en|洛伊絲·威爾遜|Lois Wilson (actress)}}及[[威廉·鮑威爾|威廉·鮑威爾]]，但此版本的存片已[[散失電影|遺失]]。

*《[[大亨小傳_(1949年電影)|大亨小傳]]》（1949年），導演是{{link-en|埃利奧特·紐根特|Elliott Nugent}}——小說第二次被搬上銀幕。{{link-en|阿倫·列特|Alan Ladd}}飾盖茨比，其他主要演員有：{{link-en|雪莉·雲達絲|Shelley Winters}}、{{link-en|比提·菲露|Betty Field}}、{{link-en|巴利·蘇里雲|Barry Sullivan}}、{{link-en|露芙·哈絲|Ruth Hussey}}、{{link-en|侯活·德·施華|Howard Da Silva}}、{{link-en|亨利·侯路|Henry Hull}}、{{link-en|加露·馬遼|Carole Mathews}}及{{link-en|麥當奴·加利|Macdonald Carey}}。因版權問題，此片並不易找。

*《[[大亨小傳_(1974年電影)|大亨小傳]]》（1974年），導演是{{link-en|傑克·克萊頓|Jack Clayton}}——該片由[[弗朗西斯·科波拉|弗朗西斯·科波拉]]改編劇本，[[羅拔·烈福|羅拔·烈福]]飾蓋斯比，其他主要演員有：[[米亚·法罗|米亚·法罗]]、[[森·和達士頓|森·和達士頓]]、[[布魯斯·丹|布魯斯·丹]]、{{link-en|侯活·德·施華|Howard Da Silva}}、{{link-en|史葛·威爾遜|Scott Wilson}}及[[嘉蓮·白烈|嘉蓮·白烈]]。

*《[[大亨小傳_(2000年電影)|大亨小傳]]》（2000年），導演是{{link-en|罗伯特·马科维茨|Robert Markowitz}}——這是[[電視電影|電視電影]]版。主演是[[陶比·史蒂芬|陶比·史蒂芬]]、[[保羅·活特|保羅·活特]]及[[米拉·索维诺|米拉·索维诺]]。

*《[[大亨小傳_(2013年電影)|大亨小傳]]》（2013年），導演是[[巴兹·鲁尔曼|巴兹·鲁尔曼]]<ref>[http://www.apdnews.com/news/33540.html 导演：尼克爱着盖茨比] {{Wayback|url=http://www.apdnews.com/news/33540.html |date=20130907035925 }}，亚太日报，2013年9月3日</ref>——原定于2012年12月25号上映的，后因3D制作原因推迟至2013年5月17日上映。主演是[[里安納度·狄卡比奧|里安納度·狄卡比奧]]、[[杜比·麥奎爾|杜比·麥奎爾]]和[[嘉莉·慕萊根|嘉莉·慕萊根]]。

===歌劇===
{{main|了不起的盖茨比 (歌剧)}}
1999年，《大亨小傳》被改編為同名歌剧，由美國作曲家[[约翰·哈比森|约翰·哈比森]]作曲；於1999年12月20日在[[紐約|紐約]][[大都會歌劇院|大都會歌劇院]]首演。
===音乐剧===
1991年，《大亨小傳》被日本[[宝冢歌剧团|宝冢歌剧团]]的专职编导[[小池修一郎|小池修一郎]]改編為同名日语音乐剧，由日本作曲家[[吉崎憲治|吉崎憲治]]、[[甲斐正人|甲斐正人]]作曲；於1991年8月8日在[[日本|日本]][[兵庫縣|兵庫縣]][[宝塚市|宝塚市]]的[[宝塚大剧场|宝塚大剧场]]首演。

